## OpenMRS Risk Register — Full Analysis

---

### RS-001 — Ransomware Attack Encrypting OpenMRS Data

**Vulnerabilities contributing:** V-005 (permissive security groups), V-010 (inadequately secured workstations), V-011 (no MFA), V-012 (inadequate security training), V-014 (backup restoration not tested), V-015 (no downtime procedures)

**Likelihood: High**

Ransomware targeting of healthcare organizations is not a rare event — it is routine. HHS reports hundreds of ransomware-related healthcare breaches annually. Small and mid-sized clinics are specifically targeted because their operational dependency on EHR systems creates leverage and their security programs tend to be less mature than larger health systems. The absence of MFA (V-011) and inadequately secured workstations (V-010) mean the initial access pathways are relatively accessible.

**Impact: High**

Successful ransomware encryption of the OpenMRS application server and database renders the system completely unavailable. With no documented downtime procedures (V-015), clinical operations would be severely disrupted. With untested backups (V-014), recovery would be uncertain and potentially prolonged — the Vermont Medical Center case from Day 29 illustrates a months-long, $63 million outcome at the severe end of this scenario.

**Overall Risk Level: HIGH**

**Response: Mitigate — Immediate Priority**

This is the highest-priority risk in the register. The mitigation actions address the vulnerability chain that enables the most damaging attack scenarios:

MFA for all OpenMRS accounts (addresses V-011) is the single highest-value control — credential compromise, the most common ransomware initial access vector, cannot be leveraged without the second factor. Target: 30 days. Endpoint security deployment — EDR and OS patching on all clinic workstations (addresses V-010) — removes the primary malware delivery pathway. Target: 60 days. S3 Object Lock on backup files (addresses V-014) prevents ransomware deletion of the recovery option. Quarterly restoration testing establishes confidence that recovery is actually achievable. Target: 45 days. Downtime procedure documentation (addresses V-015) ensures clinical operations can continue during an outage rather than halting completely. Target: 60 days. Security awareness and phishing simulation training (addresses V-012). Target: 90 days.

**Residual risk after mitigation: Moderate.** MFA and endpoint security significantly reduce successful initial access likelihood. Backup isolation and tested restoration significantly reduce impact. Residual risk reflects that determined attackers can still find access vectors and no control eliminates the threat entirely.

