## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The **2020 Universal Health Services ransomware attack** — covered on Day 3 and referenced in Day 38's risk register — illustrates what the RS-001 scenario looks like at enterprise scale. UHS's three-week recovery and estimated $67 million cost resulted from an attack that followed a well-documented chain exploiting vulnerabilities that security professionals had identified and discussed. The vulnerabilities enabling the attack — inadequate network segmentation, insufficient endpoint protection, no MFA — were not unknown. They were documented risks that had not been prioritized for remediation before the attack materialized.

The lesson is not that UHS failed to identify the risk. It is that identification without prioritization and action produces the same outcome as not identifying the risk at all. The risk register is only valuable if it drives a committed remediation timeline — which is why each RS in today's register has an explicit target date attached to the mitigation actions, not just a general commitment to address it eventually.

